-- PRESS DIGEST - RUSSIA - April 4
-- 
-- Fri Apr 04, 2014 05:37AM EDT
-- None



MOSCOW, April 4 (Reuters) - The following are some of the leading stories in Russia's newspapers on Friday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

VEDOMOSTI www.vedomosti.ru - Russia's largest bank Sberbank <SBER.MM> has filed a 19 billion rouble ($535 million) lawsuit against Omsk-based company Mostovik, one of the contractors that built Olympic facilities in Sochi, the daily says. - Employees of the Ukrainian subsidiary of Raiffeisen bank in the Crimean city of Sevastopol have asked Russian banks preparing to open in the city to hire them, the daily writes, after Raiffeisen closed all but six out of 32 Crimean branches.  - The number of smartphones supporting 4G LTE networks sold in Russia doubled in the first quarter of 2014 year-on-year, the paper says.  KOMMERSANT www.kommersant.ru - Russia's lower house of parliament has prepared amendments to the anti-terrorist law and extended the list of related crimes, the paper writes, in order to crack down on protests similar to those seen on Kiev's Maidan square. - The governor of the Volgograd region Andrei Bocharov, appointed by President Vladimir Putin on Wednesday, has described the region's financial state as catastrophic, the paper writes. - The Russian government on Thursday has designated each Crimean district as a region qualifying for economic and social support, the daily reports. - Russia ranks 80 out of 132 in the World Social Progress Index. The main reasons for the low ranking are poor ecology and healthcare, lack of tolerance and threats to people's security, the daily says.